  {
    "id": "koc2012-q014",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "dns",
    "stem": "The main function of the DNS server in the Internet Computing is:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "To convert IP addresses to hostnames",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "To convert PC identification",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "To connect your terminal or PC to the Internet world",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "To resolve hostname to IP address",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "DNS's main job is forward resolution: it maps a hostname such as www.example.com to an IP address so packets can actually be routed. Option A is the trap, IP to hostname is reverse DNS (PTR lookup), a secondary capability rather than the main function.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KOC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2012,
      "originalNumber": 14
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
